GLM vs ML: The Real Trade-Off
✅ Core idea:

GLMs prioritise interpretability, stability, and regulatory acceptance, while ML models prioritise predictive accuracy and flexibility.


🔍 1. Technical comparison























































Aspect                  GLM (e.g. Poisson, Gamma)            ML (e.g. GBM, XGBoost)
Structure              Parametric (linear in parameters)    Non-parametric
Relationships          Pre-defined (you specify)            Learns automatically
Interpretability        High (coefficients)                Low–medium (black box)
Feature interactions    Must be manually added             Automatically captured
Handling non-linearity  Needs transformations              Naturally handles
Overfitting              Lower (with regularisation)        Higher risk
Performance              Good baseline                      Often higher
Stability                High                              Can be unstable
Regulatory acceptance    Strong                             More scrutiny

🧠 2. When you would use GLM (very important)
✅ Use GLM when:
🔹 A. Regulatory environment is strict

Insurance pricing (FCA, Solvency II, GDPR)
Need:

Explainability
Auditability



👉 GLMs are easy to:

Justify
Document
Defend


🔹 B. You need transparency

Can clearly say:

“+10% premium due to age band”




🔹 C. Dataset is messy or limited

GLMs are:

More robust
Less sensitive to noise




🔹 D. Business stakeholders need clarity

Easier to communicate to:

Underwriters
Risk teams




💬 Good line:

“GLMs are often the default in regulated pricing because they balance performance with explainability and governance requirements.”


🚀 3. When you would use ML
✅ Use ML when:
🔹 A. You have large, rich datasets

Many features
Complex interactions


🔹 B. There are strong non-linear relationships

Example:

Risk varies non-linearly with age




🔹 C. You need incremental performance gains

Even small improvements → large financial impact


🔹 D. You can manage explainability

Using:

SHAP
Partial dependence plots




💬 Good line:

“I would consider ML models where there is clear evidence of non-linear relationships or interaction effects that a GLM cannot easily capture.”


⚖️ 4. The REAL trade-offs (what interviewers care about)
🔥 A. Accuracy vs Explainability

ML → higher predictive power
GLM → easier to explain

👉 In regulated pricing:

Explainability often wins unless performance gap is significant


🔥 B. Flexibility vs Control

ML:

Learns everything (including noise, bias)


GLM:

You control structure



👉 Risk:

ML can learn undesirable relationships (bias/proxies)


🔥 C. Performance vs Fairness

ML may:

Use subtle proxies (postcode patterns, etc.)


Harder to detect bias


🔥 D. Speed vs Governance effort

GLM:

Faster to validate and approve


ML:

Requires:

Explainability layer
More validation
More documentation






🧠 5. Best practice (what strong candidates say)
✅ Hybrid approach

“I typically start with a GLM as a baseline, then benchmark against ML models.”

Step-by-step:

Build GLM (interpretable baseline)
Build ML model (e.g. GBM)
Compare:

Performance uplift
Stability


Assess:

Is uplift material?
Is it explainable?


Decide:

Stick with GLM OR
Use ML with controls




✅ Advanced approach (very strong answer)

Use ML to:

Discover interactions


Then:

Feed insights into GLM



👉 This gives:

Interpretability + better performance


🧠 6. Regulatory lens (this is what gets you hired)
Under GDPR / FCA expectations:
GLM ✅

Transparent
Easy to explain
Lower risk

ML ⚠️

Must justify:

Why complexity is needed


Must ensure:

Explainability
Fairness
No hidden bias




💬 Strong line:

“In a regulated environment, I would only deploy an ML model if I can demonstrate that the performance uplift is meaningful and that the model remains explainable, fair, and appropriately governed.”


🎤 💬 Interview-ready answer
⭐ Question: “Would you use GLM or ML?”

I would typically start with a GLM as a baseline because it provides strong interpretability, stability, and aligns well with regulatory expectations. I would then benchmark it against machine learning models such as gradient boosting to assess whether there is a meaningful improvement in predictive performance.
If the ML model offers significant uplift, I would evaluate whether it can be made sufficiently explainable using techniques such as SHAP values, and whether it introduces any fairness or bias concerns.
In a regulated pricing context, the decision ultimately depends on balancing performance with transparency, fairness, and governance, and I would only adopt a more complex model if it can be robustly justified and controlled.


